text.text:
Very old temple believed to be consecrated during Tretayuga, the rituals and customs has been set by Parasurama maharshi.
Temple architecture is unique
with the fascinating mukha mandapa, sculpture work, oval Sree Kovil, big balikkall, namaskara mandapa.
Anybody who is interested in ancient Indian architecture, cannot afford to miss this temple.

text.text: It is one of the oldest temple in Kerala. The temple is a historical spot. Dedicated to Lord Shiva. Vembanad lake and Kumarakom is nearby. Very famous temple. Temple is located in kottayam district. Temple is famous for Vaikom Ashtami festival. Lord Shiva is called as 'vaikkathappan'. Very crowded temple. Always want to wait for darshan. One  of the biggest temple also. Vaikashtami is usually during november and december months.  Wedding ceremony also conducting here. A must visit temple. Suitable time to visit the temple is early morning or evening time. Temple entrance towers is in four sides.❤️ good nature beauty also🌿🌿🌴🌳❤️🥰

text.text:
Ancient Church. Miraculous experience at our visit. We recited a rosary and a priest came in and asked us a few questions and opened for us ancient Mother Mary's painting hid in the alter behind. Then he was in a trance asked Salini teacher, one of our colleagues, if she had knee pain, we know she was terribly suffering from knee pain. It has shaken all of us.
The Church had a long past history. The Vebanad lake view near adds scenic beauty to it.

text.text: The pilgrim centre claims to be one of the churches established by St. Thomas the apostle and is famously called as the ezharappally. The church also boasts of a cross established by St Thomas himself. The church is a spacious structure with beautiful works of art and architecture. The view of the lake from the church yard is a mesmerizing experience. The community there is one of the earliest Christian community in the country with a legacy from 52ad itself.

text.text: St. Thomas sailed to Kokkamangalam where he preached the gospel for about a year.[4] 1600 people converted to Christianity through him according to the narration in "Rampan Pattu", an ancient form of Christian folk-song prevalent in Kerala.He formed a Christian community at Kokkamangalam and enshrined a Cross for the faithful.This cross was later cut off by saboteurs, and thrown into the Lake Vembanad, through which it floated up to Pallippuram, where it is enshrined.

text.text: It is a highly uncommon temple that follows Advait philosophy. This temple bucks the trend by having a mirror as its idol, instead of the usual practice of consecrating idols! In 1927 June, Sree Narayana Guru, a renowned saint-scholar from Kerala, blessed the Ullala Omkaraswaram Temple on Vaikom Kumarakom road with a mirror. This temple is picturesque and many people are drawn to its tranquil atmosphere. Special Poojas take place every Thursday.
